"(1) (i) The hum of recycled air and the low, steady thrum of life support pulsed through the crystalline corridors of . Zoe moved quietly past the bioluminescent panels, her breath fogging in the cold, filtered light. Outside the reinforced domes, the ice shell of Europa glimmered with faint auroras, but inside, the sterile glow of data screens and the faint metallic tang of antiseptic made the underground world feel both alien and claustrophobic. Europa Subsurface Laboratory.\n(2) (ii) A sudden, discordant shriek ripped through the comms array. Zoe paused, her fingers tightening on the toolbelt at her hip. The main subspace antenna, its lattice of silver filaments humming with the promise of instant contact across the void, stuttered and then went silent. Alarms flashed crimson on the status board, and the air seemed to vibrate with the absence of the familiar hum. She watched as the diagnostic readouts spiraled into error, her heart hammering in a way it rarely did outside of launch simulations. witnessed a subspace antenna failure.\n(3) (iii) The failure was abrupt, violent—a collapse of potential that left the lab shrouded in a cold silence. Zoe’s breath quickened as she moved toward the control console, the emergency lights casting long, dancing shadows across the walls. Outside the main viewport, the surface of Europa was still, but the absence of subspace communication felt like a rupture in the fabric of the day itself. Every message queue blinked dead; the team’s lifelines to the outside world had vanished in an instant. December 26, 2226.\n(4) (iv. Zoe Brown."